5-21:Global strict and nonstrict oppositions are complementary cases .
5-22:Essentially, under global strict opposition the whole outcome space O becomes the Pareto optimal set as at no point in O can the negotiating parties make a joint improvement, i.e., every point in O is a Pareto efficient outcome .
5-23:In other words, under global strict opposition the outcome space O can be flattened out into a single line such that for each pair of outcomes x, y ∈ O, u1(x) < u1(y) iff u2(x) > u2(y), i.e., at every point in O, the gradient of the two utility functions point to two different ends of the line .
5-24:Intuitively, global strict opposition implies that there is no way to obtain joint improvements for both agents .
5-25:As a consequence, the negotiation degenerates to a distributive negotiation, i.e., the negotiating parties should try to claim as much shares from the negotiation issues as possible while the mediator should aim for the fairness of the division .
5-26:On the other hand, global nonstrict opposition allows room for joint improvements and all parties might be better off trying to realise the potential gains by reaching Pareto efficient agreements .
5-27:Weak and strong oppositions indicate different levels of opposition .
5-28:The weaker the opposition, the more potential gains can be realised making cooperation the better strategy to employ during negotiation .
5-29:On the other hand, stronger opposition suggests that the negotiating parties tend to behave strategically leading to misrepresentation of their respective objectives and utility functions and making joint gains more difficult to realise .
5-30:We have been temporarily making the assumption that the outcome space O is the subset of Rm .
5-31:In many real world negotiations, this assumption would be too restrictive .
5-32:We will continue our exposition by lifting this restriction and allowing discrete attributes .
5-33:However, as most negotiations involve only discrete issues with a bounded number of options, we will assume that each attribute takes values either from a finite set or from the set of real numbers R .
5-34:In the rest of the paper, we will refer to attributes whose values are from finite sets as simple attributes and attributes whose values are from R as continuous attributes .
5-35:The notions of local oppositions, i.e., strict, nonstrict, weak and strong, are not applicable to outcome spaces that contain simple attributes and nor are the notions of global weak and strong oppositions .
5-36:However, the notions of global strict and nonstrict oppositions can be generalised for outcome spaces that contain simple attributes .
5-37:DEFINITION 3 .
5-38:Given an outcome space O, the parties are in global strict opposition iff ∀x, y ∈ O, u1(x) < u1(y) iff u2(x) > u2(y) .
5-39:The parties are in global nonstrict opposition if they are not in global strict opposition .
5-40:4.1 Optimisation on simple attributes In order to extract the optimal values for a subset of attributes, in the first step of this optimisation process the mediator requests the negotiators to submit their respective utility functions over the set of simple attributes .
5-41:Let Simp ⊆ Att denote the set of all simple attributes from Att .
