6-1:In this paper we have established a framework for negotiation that is based on MCDM theory for representing the agents" objectives and utilities
6-2:The focus of the paper is on integrative negotiation in which agents aim to maximise joint gains, or create value
6-3:514 The Sixth Intl
6-4:Joint Conf
6-5:on Autonomous Agents and Multi Agent Systems (AAMAS 07) We have introduced a mediator into the negotiation in order to allow negotiators to disclose information about their utilities, without providing this information to their opponents
6-6:Furthermore, the mediator also works toward the goal of achieving fairness of the negotiation outcome
6-7:That is, the approach that we describe aims for both efficiency, in the sense that it produces Pareto optimal outcomes (i.e
6-8:no aspect can be improved for one of the parties without worsening the outcome for another party), and also for fairness, which chooses optimal solutions which distribute gains amongst the agents in some appropriate manner
6-9:We have developed a two step process for addressing the NP hard problem of finding a solution for a set of integrative attributes, which is within the Pareto optimal set for those attributes
6-10:For simple attributes (i.e
6-11:those which have a finite set of values) we use known optimisation techniques to find a Paretooptimal solution
6-12:In order to discourage agents from misrepresenting their utilities to gain an advantage, we look for solutions that are least vulnerable to manipulation
6-13:We have shown that as long as one of the simple attributes does not strongly dominate the others, then truth telling is an equilibrium strategy for the negotiators during the stage of optimising simple attributes
6-14:For non simple attributes we propose a mechanism that provides stepwise improvements to move the proposed solution in the direction of a Paretooptimal solution
6-15:The approach presented in this paper is similar to the ideas behind negotiation analysis [18]
6-16:Ehtamo et al [4] presents an approach to searching for joint gains in multi party negotiations
6-17:The relation of their approach to our approach is discussed in the preceding section
6-18:Lai et al [12] provide an alternative approach to integrative negotiation
6-19:While their approach was clearly described for the case of two issue negotiations, the generalisation to negotiations with more than two issues is not entirely clear
6-20:Zhang et at [22] discuss the use of integrative negotiation in agent organisations
6-21:They assume that agents are honest
6-22:Their main result is an experiment showing that in some situations, agents" cooperativeness may not bring the most benefits to the organisation as a whole, while giving no explanation
6-23:Jonker et al [7] consider an approach to multi attribute negotiation without the use of a mediator
6-24:Thus, their approach can be considered a complement of ours
6-25:Their experimental results show that agents can reach Paretooptimal outcomes using their approach
6-26:The details of the approach have currently been shown only for bilateral negotiation, and while we believe they are generalisable to multiple negotiators, this work remains to be done
6-27:There is also future work to be done in more fully characterising the outcomes of the determination of values for the non simple attributes
6-28:In order to provide a complete framework we are also working on the distributive phase using the mediator
